segments.text: This is very important historically because, like we said, like I said before, movies, TV were glamorizing SAC.
And they were getting the publicity during the 1950s as being, I guess, as being the elite of the armed forces.
Would you agree with that?
I was going to say, and probably rightfully so.

Because, you know, this was after the war and everything was being cut back, budget being cut back, and get back to this old bit of during time peace where everybody fights for their dollar to grow the budget.
And, you know, it immediately started and the Army was clamoring for to keep
so many divisions and so many tanks and so forth.
The Navy wanted to keep so many ships and so forth.
And we Air Force wanted an air defense command as well as SAC, as well as TAC.
And, you know, somebody had to give someplace and compromise some way.
But we in the Air Force, from the chief on down, that's where we got the basic guidance from the chief of staff of the Air Force that SAC
And the nuclear capability, if you will, strategic capability was top priority.
And for a while it was a little bit hard for tactical commanders, namely air defense and tactical command, to swallow.
See, we were trying to build up the tactical air command.
I mean the air defense command, NORAD.
Of course, this was to give warning to SAC.
So you see, there was arguments for giving us money.
We had to give warning to SAC so they could get on, so they could do their job.
So you had a rivalry right in your arms?
Rivalry is the best thing to call it, for the dollars.
Sure.
Rivalry for the dollars.
And SAGE cost us billions and billions of dollars.
SAGE?
SAGE, the Automatic Guidelines.
Were you yourself jealous of the Strategic Air Command?
A little bit.
Looking back now, I just plain old professional jealousy.
In times I remember making a comment, they act like they're not even in the regular Air Force, they're a separate Air Force.
And I think that's out of temperament and professional jealousy.
Did you ever want to apply for a SAT?
I didn't like the philosophy of command that they used in SAC.
Which was?
Fear.
I had served under ex-SAC people in my subsequent career after in the latter part of my Air Force career.
philosophy of command, and for a while it darn near demoralized the tactical aircraft.
Fortunately, that commander didn't stay long, and so we had another typical tactical aircraft commander, John Displey, who took over and got things back on an even keel.
And this gets into the philosophy of command maybe you want to talk about later on.
Well, tell me about fear.
Well, give me an example of that in the strategic air command.
You do a job, if you have an accident, this man does that, you're fired.
You're ruined.
You're career is over.
And you heard SAC commanders say that to a man?
This was the philosophy of SAC.
But you yourself heard that?
Almost.
Oh, yes.
Many people in airports at that time felt that.
I don't blame this on LeMay.
Who do you blame it on?
Other officers in the SAC hierarchy.
I don't think that exists now.
As a matter of fact, SAC has changed now, and they don't have this philosophy anymore.
We don't have this feeling in the Air Force anymore, to my knowledge.
We know the requirements of having SAC.
There's no doubt of the puts of
And now, you know, we've even got the intercontinental ballistic missiles, which are still part of SAC.

And to prove that we were right in our thinking that SAC is a predominant military power in our arsenal is that the Joint Targeting Committee is headquartered at the SAC headquarters, the Navy and the Air Force, under the Commander-in-Chief of the Strategic Air Command.
So he is the top man.
There's no doubt about it.
But going back to some of these things we've talked about, I think it is professional jealousy, but it can be expected.
But it's, I don't want to say unfounded.
SAC should be recognized.
It should be glamorized.
It should have gotten the money.
It should have been built up.
Thank God we've got it in the position it is right now.
Thank God.
But why do you say it should have had all of these things?
Well, it was fighting for the dollars.
But I mean, why do you think it should have been glamorized?
Well, you call it glamorized, are we using the proper word?
Maybe just say Department of Defense propaganda to indoctrinate the people of this country to accept it.
To indoctrinate the...
voters that the number one power tell your congressman to give money to SAC, the Air Force.
You don't buy another carrier.
This is done.
And I was all for that.
You thought that the Air Force in general should, during the 1950s, should have received more money than the Army or the Navy?
Matter of fact, because of the priority of the importance of the, if you will, we're beginning to think now in terms of deterrence.
A rhetorical question.
What do you think turned Khrushchev's ships around with taking missiles to Cuba?
It was the Strategic Air Command nuclear call.
Well, what about the...
Navy admiral that would respond.
It was the fact that we had eight aircraft carriers off the coast of Cuba blocking the way of those freighters.
Well, sure.
As a matter of fact, I was part of, where was I when that happened?
How would you answer that question?
Well, it was natural for the Admiral to say that.
Oh, okay.
But why didn't that Admiral do anything?
He wasn't supposed to do anything until he got directions from the President of the United States.

The President of the United States, probably in his frantic telephone conversation with Khrushchev, and I don't know, I can't confirm this because I've heard it secondhand, but I understand it was a red telephone hotline between Khrushchev and Kennedy.
that things got really frantic and hot.
And I can imagine the things that Kenny would be saying.
Well, sure, we've got carriers out there, but I've got my nuclear fleet ready here to take off.
Now, you turn those missiles on.
Well, they were in here at the time, weren't they?
Some of them probably were.
I know that tactically we had a huge tactical air force for all practical purposes assembled and deployed in the southern reaches of Florida, besides all those carriers down in the Navy and Sea.
We were prepared.
That was a proof of stage.
Okay, now let's go back and talk about, change the topic for a minute to your career.
You've been a full colonel now for about 13 years.
Sure were.
You were a full colonel from 44 to 57.
That's right.
Well, were you starting to wonder if you were ever going to be promoted again?
Oh, yeah.
I was a normal, typical colonel.
It entered into my mind, and there were two or three promotions, two or three years before I got it, that really I did wonder.
It's typical, normal.
Well, you had been in now for 18 years in the service.
But you look at those 18 years.
How long am I in those 18 years without a full colonel?
That's something unusual.
See, I got in right at the start of the war, so I was a full colonel in 1944.
You'd been a full colonel for 13 of the 18 years that you were in the service.
Right.
And so I was wondering if, you know, they passed you over so many times.
I don't think I was ever passed over.
I look at it that way.
I just wasn't to be chosen yet.
That's the way I look at it.
Oh, is there any possibility of jeopardy that they might order you into retirement unless you made Brigadier General?
I never, no, I never.
That never in my mind, my career.
What?
Legally, could it have happened?
No, no.
Okay.
There's just so many spots open.
Yeah, I'm not...
I'm just wondering about this.
You're asking questions I'm answering.
Just so you know, there was nothing like that.
Okay, but were you... Later on, you know, rules and regulations were set up for promotion.
In later years, we're actually passed over a certain number.
As a matter of fact, my brother was passed over, and that's
Before he was forced out actually by the law, he did retire.
Well, when were those retirement laws established?
I thought they were established in the 50s.
I don't know.
Well, at any rate, that wasn't up to me.
And I never worried about it.
OK.
Did you want to become a general?
Oh, certainly.
As a matter of fact, I had the aspiration to become a four-star general.
You did?
I'm sure I was typical.
Ambitious?
You considered yourself ambitious.
Oh, absolutely.
Dedicated.
Tell me about when you learned that you were going to be promoted to brigadier general.
How'd you find out?
Let me see.
How did I find that out?
I think I got a call from a general someplace on the, well, maybe Washington.
Probably Washington.
Got a call from him.
Just called me at my headquarter there at... No, you had to be in Colorado.
I said in the airport today.
I was in Colorado.
Yeah, you were in Colorado.
And he called me and said, congratulations, Charles.
Something like that.
That's the first indication.
I knew the list was coming out.
Who was it?
General... Four-star general.
Moe Preston, M-O-E Preston, P-R-E-S-T-O-N.
I'd worked for him.
He was my boss, first boss at Northeast Air Command up at Newton.
When he called me, I think when he called me, he was four-star general, yeah.
And congratulations.
Now, I think, Terry, I think that's the first indication.
Then General Partridge...
met me in a hall, and somehow I knew, I remember this one.
General Partridge met me and made this comment to me.
I knew I was promoted.
He shook hands and said, congratulations, Charlie.
He says, you know, now you're general officer, you ain't going to have any fun anymore.
Laughed.
And then they began to come from all directions.
Was that the same day?
Oh, yeah.
Oh, yeah.
What were your feelings when you found out?
Oh, of course I was elated.

I had anticipated, you know, we, when the promotion list was getting ready to come out for General General's Day, the colonels, boy, they follow them and they'll snoot and they'll do everything, you know, to find out when they're going to be out, you know, and they listen and do everything you can to find out things.
But I knew the announcement was imminent and, you know, I was waiting and then, of course, I got this
earlier call from one of the, I think it was the Pentagon, no question it was the Pentagon, but at any rate, someplace on the East Coast, he called me and congratulated me.
I'm pretty sure that was his first indication.
The first thing I did was went in my office and called Doris and told her about it.
And of course it wasn't to be effective until, when did, well, it wasn't to be effective until later on when I was going to move.
It was effective 30th of August 1957.
Yeah, but the date of the promotion was real early.
That's right, yeah.
30th of August.
And I was to take over command of the 25th Air Division, but they were going to send me up there earlier before I could put the star on.
Oh, the date of rank?
Yeah.
It was way back earlier, isn't it?
1st of August, 58?
No, wait a minute.
Maybe that's the range you're talking about.
No, no.
That's...
No, the date of rank, the temporary promotion was August 30, 1957.
That's when you could put your star on it.
Yeah, it's temporary.
But I was due to go up to, I had
Simultaneously with that promotion, and that's probably one of the reasons I promoted it, because they were going to give me a command of the 25th Air Division up at Tacoma, Washington.
And you had to be a Brigadier General commander of the division.
So that's part of the reason I'm sure I was promoted.
But I wanted to put the star on and arrive as a Brigadier General.

So I asked, and as a matter of fact, I even remember talking to, I think it was Ken Berkman about it, my boss, and he agreed with me, and, well, we just get you already delayed, you go up there, get your star on first, and then you go up there.
So that's where we did that.
Oh, did you?
I arrived with my star on.
Great.
It's more effective.
More effective as far as leadership?
Yeah.
And at reception, you know, the civilian community,
General Bond here, whether it was Colonel Bond here, and I don't know if I was in before, but he made general vision.
Sure.
Now tell me about that command, 25th Air Division.
Well, that was my first command as a general officer, and of course it was... Two years, 57 to 59.
Getting used to being a brigadier general was almost... Getting used to being a general officer and
was almost first priority with me from the standpoint of my entire responsibility commanding my Confederate agents.
By the way, I relieved a general who was commanding .
Tell me about getting used to being a general officer.
What were the problems?
Well, I don't know whether you call them problems or not.
It's just acting the part.
of a general, and I guess acting as part of what you consider to be the ideal type of a general.
In other words, I guess all of us had in mind what a real general was and how you would act and so forth, and then you sort of modeled yourself after that.
At least that was my feeling, and I think many others felt the same way.
And then how did you model yourself?
Who was the ideal general to you?
Did you model yourself?
Well, see, that's it.
You think of many generals that you knew before and how they acted.
Of course, I did come from Norad where I had a great deal of respect for General Cartridge, a very fine man who conducted himself as a dignified, very fine man.
Didn't smoke, drank little, was a fine physical specimen, and a
would still fly an airplane.
And then I remember an old gentleman, a hard man, hard but fair, demanded competence, excellent performance, that type of thing, but treated people fair.
Just hard but fair.
I guess that's sort of my feeling, being hard but fair.
In other words, you have more accepted the LeMay?
You more modeled yourself after LeMay than after Partridge?
No, I won't say that.
I guess a combination of Chenault, LeMay, Partridge, Charlie Myers, a terrific man whom I worked under, a Northeasterly man who was
went by, people knew him as Uncle Charlie.
Kind, gentle, fine old man.
Terrific.
You name it.
The qualities, all the qualities that you would, you can think of, you know, I thought of them as various generals.
And even after all that, I guess I settled down to just being old Charlie Bond after all, after a while.
Doing what I thought was right, handing people and making decisions.
I had a very fine, tactically oriented command.
I had one of the best air defense divisions in the entire United States.
Did you ever want to talk about that?
Did you find it difficult to assume the role as a general?
No.
No.
I was prepared for it.
Okay, tell me about your division.
How large was it?
What was the mission?
The mission included...
I believe when I took over this command, it was still CONAD.
We hadn't actually officially announced the NORAD organization, which would have included part of Canada later on.
When I first took it over, I included...
I take it back.
It was NORAD, yeah.
My command included a line on the map.
It went up...

north of Vancouver, matter of fact, probably 30 or 40 miles, maybe 50, 60 miles north of the Canadian border to include two or three radar sites, and then east-west from the ocean, extending out the ocean, you know, to include early warning naval ships, then over to include part of Montana, then down south, including Idaho, then across, including the northern part of Oregon,
then out to sea again.

So it was really the northwestern sector of the United States, and it was, if you go right straight down south of me for the western part of the United States, I had my division for the northwest, the 28th division for the central part of the west coast, San Francisco primarily, then the 27th division for the southern part of the United States, in the west, primarily Los Angeles.
for geography-wise, that's about the way it was lined up.
And I wore two or three hats, if you will.
I was a combined commander, General Charles Bond, commander of the 25th NORAD Division, which included Canada.
I had a fighter squadron and two or three radars there.
I had one.
I owned the base, the big base at McCord.
the little base north there called Payne Air Force Base up towards the northern border of the United States towards Canada.
I was a tenant on a SAC B-52 base over in western Washington at Larson Air Force Base.
I had National Guard units at Geiger Air Force Base under me, fighter units.
I had, oh, I'd say at least five or six radar sites
six or seven right now, throughout Washington, the state of Washington, and Oregon under me.
Montana and Idaho.
I'd say... You said you wore two or three hats.
What was your other one?
My second hat was a Joint Commander.
Army and Navy.
I had, by the way, I had operational control of the Canadian Forces.
I had operational control.
I didn't command them, but I had operational control over them.
I was commander of the, joint commander of the 25th Con-Ad Division, which included the United States Army and the United States Air Force units.
I had Nike
ground-to-air missiles, ground-to-air missiles, surface-to-air missiles under me.
And at that time, Ajax later on became Nike nuclear chips.
And then I wore a third hat as the Air Force commander of the 25th Air Division, ADC, which is just the Air Force units and radar sites.
And I had operational control over a Navy
early warning radar ship destroyer type out to the sea off of the coast of northern Oregon and Washington.
Then I also had operational control over what we called an AEW, Airborne Early Warning and Control Air Force aircraft.
out of air defense command with radar flying back and forth in the area for air-to-air, well, air coverage, extending our radar coverage to the seaboard.
So I had quite a big organization, and I can't remember exactly.
I'd say it had to be 15,000, 20,000 people.
This is a tremendous leap in responsibility for us.
How'd you like all the additional responsibility?
Well, it's a challenge.
I liked it.
I had to work.
I accepted it.
And my wife
detected the true dedication and the work and my position.
You know, it involved her and I found it disgusting, the higher responsibility we had in the Air Force and my military career.
We talked about it many times.
And of course, I was the number one Air Force man in that area, ranking Air Force man, so I had the leading
responsibility in relation to the civilians in the community.
Yeah, tell me about that.
Did you have any problems with the civilians?
No.
As a matter of fact, I've never had any problems with any civilians in the community.
It's something you have to contend with, though, and you have to recognize.
I had some heated arguments with a congresswoman from the state of Oregon one time, Edith Green, about an air defense, my air defense unit at the airport at Portland, Oregon.
She was trying to get us out of there.
Why?
She just didn't want us in there.
It involved too much of a problem for the city and also messed up the, supposedly took occupied, widely needed facilities for the commercial airlines and other political reasons.
I guess at the closest I came, really, to locking horns with a politician.
But I kept my temper, and I'm glad I did.
But if I ever did dislike the congressman, the congresswoman, the senator, that was the one.
You thought she was unreasonable?
I thought she was wrong.
Of course, she had her political reasons, and I understand the power of politics, but I had my military responsibilities.
You remained in that job for about two years, and then you shifted to the 28th Air Division in California, Hamilton Air Force Base.
Why'd they shift you?
I'd been up there for
couple of years, and after you've been in the command for a while, you know, maybe look forward to going to another one.
But I loved California, and Hamilton Air Force Base was the most choice air base in the entire United States.
Why?
One of the most beautiful, convenient, to that lovely city of San Francisco.
Climate-wise, it was better than that rainy area of Northwest United States and Washington, but beautiful.

and also I was very close to General Parker who was then the commander of Western Air Defense Force who commanded the three divisions from the north to the south and he and I were very close mutually respected each other and that job came open and we liked each other and
He knew I loved Hamilton.
I'd done a good job, and I'd been up in Washington for two years, and the way things go, he gave me the job.
Well, either at Hamilton or on my board in Washington, were there any major problems that you had to overcome?
No.
Essentially, this was the same type of job, exactly.
It was a similar type of an air division, but in a different location.
You felt a little bit greater responsibility for protecting, let's say, a huge area like San Francisco versus, let's say, Seattle.
But on the other hand, Seattle had terrific aircraft industry.
And SAC bases in it.
Of course, now I had SAC bases protecting the 28th Division area.
So really, it's essentially exactly the same job.
I was living closer to my boss, my headquarter, as a matter of fact, on the same airbag.
He would come over and see me and give me
of proper management.
Same job.
As a matter of fact, I felt much more secure because of the experience of wearing my star for a few years in the Command and Air Division.
I took over the 28th without a problem.
As a matter of fact, it was a little bit smaller in size and units and radar sites in the 25th Air Division.
And I didn't have the Canadians under me then.
How did you get along with the Canadians when you were in Washington?
Fine.
Typical great people.
Well, were you sorry to leave Hamilton in October 1960 when you went to Italy for three years?
No, I figured I was due for an overseas assignment.
Here again, when I came up, I had a chance to take my family.
And here again, see, it was a NATO job.
It was combined.
It was shape.
Shape.
And here I see I was in a combined command.
I was wearing a NORAD hat.
I'd been operating with Canadian forces, another nation.
I'd had experience a long, long time.
But now you were the deputy commander.
Yep.
And the commander was what, a two-star general?
No, a general.
Bianchi was a lieutenant general, three-star general in the Italian Air Force.
But he was commanding the Fifth Allied Tactical Air Force of the southern area of shape.
What did we call it?
Yeah, north, central, and south.
South Forces, what economy is referred to them as South Forces of NATO, which included the Army, Navy, and Air Forces.
Greeks, Turks, Italian, American, British, you name it, NATO.
In a sense, you lost your own command to a new job.
Did you resent losing time?
I figured this was definitely a step up, because this was NATO.
Sure.
This was a...
Allied Tactical Air Force.
I was going to an Air Force level from a division level, so I was going on.
And I never dreamed of the problems I would have when I took over this job.
It was a, the move was a fantastic journey.
We traveled by ship with my family on a first class USS Independence.
First, look at TB Love Boat today and see that ship.
Well, that's the type of ship we were on.
Had my whole family with me and shipped my car and all.
Treated royally.
SS in the family.
It wasn't an United States ship.
Well, SS, yeah.
And commercial ship.
Big luxury liner.
On the way we stopped at Casablanca and got ashore.
That's the first state my wife had any foreign country and was aghast at it.
And then we stopped for a second at Gibraltar, then on to Majorca, and then to Naples, and then to basically Dr. Genova.
We met there by accident.
some of the staff that I was taking over, and then we drove across in a car to Vicenza, Italy, where I was there for the next three years.
Very interesting assignment.
Charlie?
Yep.
Do you want to change the water?
Oh, yeah.
You mentioned problems and all kinds of problems in Italy with NATO.
What were they?
That I hadn't anticipated.
And you had not anticipated?
What were these problems?

Well, upon arriving at Vicenza, a little town about 30 minutes driving west from Venice, in the northern area of Italy, just at the foothills of the Alps, just an ideal place, geographical-wise, in Europe, to be assigned with my family, naturally.
was the happiest man in the world.
I hadn't been there 24 hours when I met the man I was replacing, and he briefed me on his boss, who was to be my boss, Lieutenant General Bianchi.
That is wrong.
B-I-A-N-C-H-I.
If there ever was a Hitler fascist, this man was.
No kidding.
The general I relieved, a brigadier general, United States Air Force,
That's one reason he was being reassigned, and the spot had to be filled, and it was a NATO assignment.
He wouldn't speak to General Bianchi.
He would not even go into his office.
They hated each other so much.
Really?
And he briefed me on the type of man this gentleman was, and I didn't know this.
Nobody ever told me.
And I was shocked.
They must have known this back at the Pentagon.
I'm sure they did.
Why they assigned you?
Because you'd had so many international contacts?
And had been on combined staff, worked with other nationals.
So here was another national, a commander that I was the vice commander on.
And of course, I learned as time went on that no wonder.
guy wouldn't speak to him, and I don't blame him.
Had I been a different person, I guess I wouldn't have spoken with the man.
But he hated, there's no doubt this man in his heart had to hate Americans from the standpoint of the typical jealous battalion, hating an American.
but it stemmed from his background as a fascist, I'm sure.
He was the tactical air commander in support of General Rommel for the African campaign against the American and British forces.
That's how high a position he was.
How the heck did he ever get a position in charge of NATO?
Well, actually, in this position, though, and on through the end of the war, you think, why shouldn't he be chief of staff of the Italian Air Force?
And, you know, way high up,
But he wasn't, and he was only lieutenant colonel.
But it's obvious his personality and just a nasty, nasty, arrogant, fierce, savage man, his personality.
Not physically, but nasty in his talk.
He could speak perfect English, but proud of it.
A typical arrogant, strutting, ill-duty type.
I hated his guts.
Put that in there.
That's awfully strong.
And subsequently, of course, I found out that he was known all over NATO as a respected person.
And your old Charlie Bond was his vice commander.
How did he get the job of being in charge of the southern section of NATO with that personality?
He had had previous jobs in NATO headquarters, but it's obviously because of his personality he couldn't get along.
They didn't want him.
But he was a very capable tactical commander.
There's no doubt there wasn't another general in the Italian Air Force that could even touch him in tactical experience and know-how.
They couldn't.
There was none that I knew of or met that could even touch him.
He was, no doubt, because of his experience and background.
He had been in the Civil War in Spain, on the side of the Pacific.
At times he'd get off on the Il Duce, and no doubt he still respected the Il Duce.
What did he say about it?
He just respected him.
Nothing direct about, I love the man, nothing like that, but his conversation always about the Il Duce was, you know, it was obvious that...
He's a fascist.
How could you tell?
He was a typical, anything you've ever read about the arrogant, fascist type of person, this is the way he acted.
You've seen movies of him.
You've seen movies of Ducey, El Ducey.
This is the way he acted.
This was his personality.
He would, in inspecting troops walking down a line, he'd actually strut
like maybe the way a movie star would strut, you know, over, just emoting.
You can tell the way I'm talking how I felt about the man.
My first reception by him was, had I not been told about the man, I would have never suspected it the first time I met him.
I was received in his office with open arms, very polite, very condescending,
And looking back now, getting ready to shove the knife up my rear end and down my back.
Literally hated Americans.
My boss down the line, American Air Force, United States Air Force's wife, Lieutenant General Swafford, who was Commander Air South, actually was commander of him, see, in the NATO command.
Commander Air South
was the Air Force component of AFSAL, which was the southern region of Europe of the NATO command, vis-a-vis AFSANT, Armed Forces Central Europe, and AFNORTH, Armed Forces Northern Europe.
That was NATO, in effect.
Then, of course, you had some other commands.
But essentially, that was Europe.
I was vice commander of the 5th Allied Tactical Air Force

under air air force's south general swafford who was always an uh american general that's the way the village were assigned the commander of the fifth a-tap was essentially the italian air force italy so naturally it was italian general the commander of the sixth a-tap uh the other air force of the uh air south was in izmir turkey and uh was commanded by a
edict, an agreement, by an American general, American Air Force general.
That was a lineup.
And it consisted of the Greek and Turkish Air Forces.
Fifth ATF and Sixth ATF.
Immediately to our north in Central Forces was the Fourth ATF, which was also commanded by an American Air Force general.
But that's the way the setup was.
Were most of your problems on this job caused by Bianchi?
Oh, absolutely.
I didn't have any problem whatsoever in Italy.
As far as the job itself was concerned, were there any problems, or were they all this man?
Oh, there were some problems in cooperation with the Italian Army.
I think probably caused by the feelings of the

United States Army component, which was really a surface-to-surface missile unit at Pachinza, a nuclear-tipped outfit, and working with an Italian counterpart of the same type of an outfit, where really they could help instruct them and train them and so forth.
And they were the members of the Army forces.
of AFSAL, Armed Forces of the South.

And the Army General of the Italian Army and General Bianchi, the Air Force commander, they had jealousy, very obvious, much more so than those of, let's say, the Army and the Air Force, the United States forces, let's say, back in the United States.
We didn't know what professional jealousy was.
You see that over there.
